{"key":"processedPost-10484925","value":{"id":10484925,"first":10471855,"last":10491595,"when":1244687765,"utime":"06/11/09 05:36 AM","content":"The figure of 100 feet per minute of airspeed is correct.&nbsp; However, for a 4 square foot filter, I'd go a tad over 400 cfm, because we don't live in a perfect world.&nbsp; There is resistance and drag to contend with, and you'll lose a little bit of flow in your prefilter, which is necessary if you want your expensive laminar flow filter to last a long time.&nbsp; I'd look for a blower with around 500 cfm at .9\" to 1.1\" of static pressure and you'll be much better off.<br /><br />I wouldn't waste time building anything but a <i>laminar</i> flow hood with a certified filter.&nbsp; The time and trouble are worth more than the savings on a cheapie that could lead to failure down the road.&nbsp; Don't forget to build a plenum behind the filter at least as large as the filter itself.&nbsp; The plenum is important for achieving laminar flow.<br />RR","title":"Re: Flowhood"}}